Hi, in `car-lease-demo` example there is a code (file `Server_Side/blockchain/transactions/CRUD/read.js`):
```
var cert = block.transactions[i].cert;
cert = cert.replace(/(.{1,64})/g, '$1\n');
cert = '-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----\n' + cert + '-----END CERTIFICATE-----\n'
block.transactions[i].cert = x509.parseCert(cert);
block.transactions[i].caller = block.transactions[i].cert.subject.commonName;
block.transactions[i].failed = false;
``` 
In version 0.6 `subject.commonName` contains `Transaction certificate`, not the correct caller name. I’m searching for another way to save caller name in certificate. And my idea is to use certificate attributes. It works ok in chaincode but I can’t understand how to parse attributes in JS code. Can anyone help?
Thanks

